stershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kilkenny, County Donegal, Ireland":"Kilkenny, County Donegal, Ierland","Urswick, Lancashire (now Cumbria), England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St Michael on Wyre, Lancashire, England":"St Michael's on Wyre, Lancashire, England","Of Manor Of, Rawcliffe, Lancashire, England":"Rawcliffe, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1345–1428":"1345–1428","1332–1423":"1332–1423","1376–Male":"1376–Deceased","1325–1366":"1325–1366","1332–1390":"1332–1390","1325":"1325","1423":"1423","1345":"1345","1366":"1366","1376":"1376","1332":"1332","ABT 1366":"about 1366","<1376>":"1376","24 March 1390":"24 March 1390","1428":"1428","1390":"1390","Warwick Lanthony, Gloucester, Gloucestershire, GBR":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Kilkenny, County Donegal, Ireland":"Kilkenny, County Donegal, Ireland","Urswick, Lancashire (now Cumbria), England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","St Michael on Wyre, Lancashire, England":"St Michael's on Wyre, Lancashire, England","Of Manor Of, Rawcliffe, Lancashire, England":"Rawcliffe, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘Morning dew’; also ‘generosity’."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Johanna de Hertforth was born in 1345, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert de Hertforth, was 21 and her mother, Lady Elizabeth Anne de Darcy, Countess of Badsworth and Ormond, was 13. She married Sir Thomas Urswick of Badsworth. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1428, in her hometown, at the age of 83."},"et":{"1345–1428":"1345–1428","1332–1423":"1332–1423","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1325–1366":"1325–1366","1332–1390":"1332–1390","1325":"1325","1423":"1423","1345":"1345","1366":"1366","1376":"1376","1332":"1332","ABT 1366":"umbes 1366","<1376>":"1376","24 March 1390":"24. märts 1390","1428":"1428","1390":"1390","Warwick Lanthony, Gloucester, Gloucestershire, GBR":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kilkenny, County Donegal, Ireland":"Kilkenny, County Donegal, Iirimaa","Urswick, Lancashire (now Cumbria), England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Michael on Wyre, Lancashire, England":"St Michael's on Wyre, Lancashire, England","Of Manor Of, Rawcliffe, Lancashire, England":"Rawcliffe, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1345–1428":"1345–1428","1332–1423":"1332–1423","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1325–1366":"1325–1366","1332–1390":"1332–1390","1325":"1325","1423":"1423","1345":"1345","1366":"1366","1376":"1376","1332":"1332","ABT 1366":"noin 1366","<1376>":"1376","24 March 1390":"24. maaliskuuta 1390","1428":"1428","1390":"1390","Warwick Lanthony, Gloucester, Gloucestershire, GBR":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kilkenny, County Donegal, Ir